uld hardly have been avoided in a sexist culture, and recognizing the truth of such a claim does not commit us to condemn every male philosopher and theologian who has written on the problem. It suggests, rather, that we may get a clearer view of evil if we take a different standpoint. The standpoint I take here will be that of women; that is, I will attempt to describe evil from the perspective of women's experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminism. 0aGood and evil. 0aWomen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aaging.  aangel in the house.  acruelty.  acultural narratives.  adomesticity.  aethical terror.  aeve.  aevil.  afemininity.  afeminism.  afeminist theory.  agender roles.  agender studies.  agender.  agood and evil.  ahorror.  ahuman evil.  ajung.  alilith.  aliterary criticism.  aliterature.  amadonna whore dichotomy.  amadonna.  amasculinity.  amorality.  amotherhood.  amyth.  anonfiction.  apain.  apatriarchy.  aphilosophy.  aproblem of evil.  areligion.  aretribution.  asocial science.  asupernatural.  aterror.  aterrorism.  avengeance.  awomen as evil.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091120840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911208/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY